00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,326
Chapter 82 - The Honor and Glory of Wailing. There are some enterprises in which a careful disorderliness is the true method.

2
00:00:08,928 --> 00:00:15,660
The more I dive into this matter of wailing, and push my researches up to the very spring head of it so much,

3
00:00:15,640 --> 00:00:19,166
the more am I impressed with its great honorableness and antiquity.

4
00:00:19,507 --> 00:00:35,775
And especially when I find so many great demigods and heroes, prophets of all sorts, who one way or other have shed distinction upon it, I am transported with the reflection that I myself belong, though but subordinately, to so emblazoned a fraternity.

5
00:00:35,755 --> 00:00:46,859
The gallant Perseus, a son of Jupiter, was the first whaleman, and to the eternal honor of our calling be it said, that the first whale attacked by our brotherhood was not killed with any sordid intent.

6
00:00:47,581 --> 00:00:55,418
Those were the nightly days of our profession, when we only bore arms to succor the distressed and not to fill men's lamp-feeders.

7
00:00:55,398 --> 00:00:58,762
Everyone knows the fine story of Perseus and Andromeda.

8
00:00:59,243 --> 00:01:04,289
How the lovely Andromeda, the daughter of a king, was tied to a rock on the seacoast.

9
00:01:04,850 --> 00:01:14,683
And as Leviathan was in the very act of carrying her off, Perseus, the prince of whalemen, intrepidly advancing, harpooned the monster and delivered and married the maid.

10
00:01:15,504 --> 00:01:21,912
It was an admirable artistic exploit, rarely achieved by the best harpooners of the present day.

11
00:01:21,892 --> 00:01:44,380
Inasmuch as this Leviathan was slain at the very first dart, and let no man doubt this archite story, for in the ancient Joppa, now Jaffa, on the Syrian coast, in one of the pagan temples, there stood for many ages the vast skeleton of a whale, which the city's legends and all the inhabitants asserted to be the identical bones of the monster that Perseus slew.

12
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:50,127
When the Romans took Joppa, the same skeleton was carried to Italy in triumph.

13
00:01:50,107 --> 00:01:54,449
What seems most singular and suggestively important in this story is this.

14
00:01:55,354 --> 00:01:58,108
It was from Joppa that Jonah set sail.

15
00:01:58,949 --> 00:02:07,940
Akin to the adventure of Perseus and Andromeda, indeed, by some supposed to be indirectly derived from it, is that famous story of St.

16
00:02:07,980 --> 00:02:11,705
George and the dragon, which dragon I maintain to have been a whale.

17
00:02:12,366 --> 00:02:18,393
For in many old chronicles whales and dragons are strangely jumbled together and often stand for each other.

18
00:02:18,934 --> 00:02:26,543
Thou art as a lion of the waters, and as a dragon of the sea, saith Ezekiel, hereby plainly meaning a whale.

19
00:02:26,523 --> 00:02:29,788
In truth, some versions of the Bible use that word itself.

20
00:02:30,790 --> 00:02:34,756
Besides, it would much subtract from the glory of the exploit had St.

21
00:02:34,796 --> 00:02:41,026
George but encountered a crawling reptile of the land instead of doing battle with the great monster of the deep.

22
00:02:41,847 --> 00:02:45,393
Any man may kill a snake, but only a Perseus, a St.

23
00:02:45,413 --> 00:02:49,399
George, a coffin have the heart in them to march boldly up to a whale.

24
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:53,205
Let not the modern paintings of this scene mislead us.

25
00:02:53,489 --> 00:03:09,642
For though the creature encountered by that valiant whaleman of old is vaguely represented of a griffon-like shape, and though the battle is depicted on land and the saint on horseback, yet considering the great ignorance of those times, when the true form of the whale was unknown to artists,

26
