and considering that as in Perseus's case, St.

27
00:03:12,625 --> 00:03:18,432
George's whale might have crawled up out of the sea on the beach, and considering that the animal ridden by St.

28
00:03:18,492 --> 00:03:29,284
George might have been only a large seal or seahorse, bearing all this in mind, it will not appear altogether incompatible with the sacred legend and the ancientist drafts of the scene.

29
00:03:29,905 --> 00:03:38,835
In fact, placed before the strict and piercing truth, this whole story will fare like that fish, flesh, and foul idol of the Philistines.

30
00:03:38,967 --> 00:03:49,190
Dagon by name, who being planted before the Ark of Israel, his horse's head and both the palms of his hands fell off from him, and only the stump or fishy part of him remained.

31
00:03:49,932 --> 00:03:56,908
Thus then, one of our own noble stamp, even a whaleman, is the tutelary guardian of England,

32
00:03:56,888 --> 00:04:02,355
and by good rights we harpooners of Nantucket should be enrolled in the most noble order of St.

33
00:04:02,396 --> 00:04:02,836
George.

34
00:04:03,517 --> 00:04:11,548
And therefore, let not the knights of that honorable company, none of whom, I venture to say, have ever had to do with a whale like their great patron.

35
00:04:12,069 --> 00:04:19,559
Let them never eye a Nantucketer with disdain, since even in our woolen frocks and tarred trousers we are much better entitled to St.

36
00:04:19,579 --> 00:04:21,782
George's decoration than they.

37
00:04:21,762 --> 00:04:42,336
Whether to admit Hercules among us or not, concerning this I long remain dubious, for though according to the Greek mythologies, that antique Crockett and Kit Carson, that brawny doer of rejoicing good deeds, was swallowed down and thrown up by a whale, still, whether that strictly makes a whaleman of him, that might be mooted.

38
00:04:42,502 --> 00:04:48,232
It nowhere appears that he ever actually harpooned his fish, unless, indeed, from the inside.

39
00:04:48,292 --> 00:04:52,779
Nevertheless, he may be deemed a sort of involuntary whaleman.

40
00:04:53,260 --> 00:04:56,786
At any rate, the whale caught him, if he did not the whale.

41
00:04:57,507 --> 00:04:59,751
I claim him for one of our clan.

42
00:04:59,731 --> 00:05:10,732
But, by the best contradictory authorities, this Grecian story of Hercules and the whale is considered to be derived from the still more ancient Hebrew story of Jonah and the whale, and vice versa.

43
00:05:11,253 --> 00:05:12,735
Certainly, they are very similar.

44
00:05:13,617 --> 00:05:16,623
If I claim the demigod then, why not the prophet?

45
00:05:17,364 --> 00:05:23,275
Nor do heroes, saints, demigods, and prophets alone comprise the whole role of our order.

46
00:05:23,255 --> 00:05:32,353
Our Grandmaster is still to be named, for like royal kings of old times, we find the headwaters of our fraternity in nothing short of the great gods themselves.

47
00:05:33,055 --> 00:05:39,508
That wondrous oriental story is now to be rehearsed from the Shastra, which gives us the dread Vishnu,

48
00:05:39,488 --> 00:05:53,734
One of the three persons in the Godhead of the Hindus gives us this divine Vishnu himself for our Lord, Vishnu, who, by the first of his ten earthly incarnations, has forever set apart and sanctified the whale.

49
00:05:54,068 --> 00:06:18,237
When Brahma, or the god of gods, saith the shastra, resolved to recreate the world after one of its periodical dissolutions, he gave birth to Vishnu to preside over the work, but the Vedas, or mystical books, whose perusal would seem to have been indispensable to Vishnu before beginning the creation, and which therefore must have contained something in the shape of practical hints to young architects,

50
00:06:18,217 --> 00:06:20,699
These Vedas were lying at the bottom of the waters.

51
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:27,767
So Vishnu became incarnate in a whale, and sounding down in him to the uttermost depths, rescued the sacred volumes.

52
00:06:28,327 --> 00:06:30,449
Was not this Vishnu a whaleman then?

53
00:06:31,090 --> 00:06:33,913
Even as a man who rides a horse is called a horseman?

54
00:06:34,413 --> 00:06:39,919
Perseus, Saint George, Hercules, Jonah, and Vishnu, there's a member role for you.

55
00:06:39,959 --> 00:06:43,262
What club but the whalemans can head off like that?

